	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row2"><span class="name"><a name="111052"></a><b>EvilNight</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">Agent of the System<br />
		<br /><img src="http://www.eqluclin.com/forum/images/avatars/bunbun.gif" alt="Avatar" class="avatar" border="0" />
		<br />Joined: 19 Jul 2003<br />Posts: 2739</span></td>
		<td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=111052&amp;sid=9963e97b7767f20618cfb558e6fe2e7f#111052"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu Mar 31, 2005 1:38 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Supreme Court hearing P2P case</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=111052&amp;sid=9963e97b7767f20618cfb558e6fe2e7f"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>     </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> My point with that is if you have no vested interest in some innate artistic talent, then I imagine it would be hard for you to understand why people may get a bit miffed when you steal their intellectual property. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
What you are saying is that since I have no idea of the amount of effort that goes into a creative work, I have no respect for the terms of the laws that protect those who have put in the time from recouping their investment. This is a rather typical baseless assumption on your part. Perhaps you should simply accept the fact that I know as much as if not more than you do about this issue, and I have rationally arrived at a vastly different set of conclusions in this arena than you have, and leave it at that. Time will tell who's beliefs are correct; the market will decide as it always does. As a thought exercise, however, you may want to consider things were <span style="font-style: italic">significantly</span> more in favor of your belief system ten years ago, and are now rapidly swinging around to my way of thinking. Such trends do not reverse easily.
<br />

<br />
If I weren't currently writing the baseline for a series of science fiction novels, you might have had a point, however tactless your accusation was. If I thought it was a dollar of work before, the reality of the job is worth a million dollars. If you'll remember, it took Tolkien decades to write his baseline for LoTR, and believe me I can see precisely why. You have to write an encyclopedia of research about your novel before you can really begin to write it. What's worse... if it's science fiction, and a new technology breaks, it can turn your vision of the future inside out and leave you with mountains of rewriting to do. <a href="http://home.earthlink.net/~judithberman/fiction/sffuture.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Scifi has lost sight of the future </a>because of that and if I write this thing that's one thing I intend to change. I have a very good understanding of the amount of work that goes into even something as simple as a novel of a few hundred pages. It is very hard work to maintain an illusion of reality and remain as factually correct as possible. Writing is sustained telepathy, one of the hardest arts there is, and there's nothing like poor prose or broken facts to break that tenuous link.
<br />

<br />
And I still support limited copyrights. I value the public domain far more than you do. I consider it far more important than any one man's work. That's the difference in philosophy between us. If what I write somehow ended up as popular as Tolkien or Star Wars, I'd voluntarily release the copyright on it after ten years (and a couple feature films; I can put that kind of money to good use for humanity) just to prove a point to people like you. I'd then be rubbing every addition to the body of the work created by other people in everyone's faces as proof that my way of thinking is more beneficial to society and the right way to go. I for one would like to live to see what kind of effect my creations would have on the creative talents of other people, and I can't do that if it is chained up in copyright law. How anyone who can create something like that can bring themselves to let it rot away that way is utterly beyond my comprehension. I can understand why corporations would treat IP that way, but not the original creator.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> It is shocking that you need to be compeled to do the morally and ethically right thing. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I don't feel it is the morally right and ethical thing. I find locking works up in copyright for extended periods of time to be unenlightened, selfish, self-centered, and morally repugnant. I find it criminal; a detriment to society. I won't concede to your views on the subject, having thoroughly considered all of your arguments and the arguments of people on your side of this issue and rejected them as irrational and bound up in inferior ways of thinking that are stuck in the past. I live in the same world that you do, as do plenty of other people who feel the same way that I do. You have to share the world with people who feel that way, so you get to suck up and cope with it just like we cope with your draconian restrictions on information. Neither one of us will ever get the laws they want; we get a halfassed compromise and a real world mess instead. Such is life, and the state of any issue.
<br />

<br />
Given enough time, the generation that grows up with this free flow of information will be making the laws and running the globe. You're fooling yourself if you think things won't change then.
<br />

<br />
Zerg is quite right, this is all a market correction, probably the largest one we will ever witness in our lifetimes. Just as linux was a free market response to Microsoft's monopoly, so too is p2p a response to the intellectual property situation. If you think it's bad now, just you wait two or three decades and listen to the screams when the pendulum swings the other way, and creative commons licensing locks the world information market into free commodities. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Raviel, seriously bud, you are living in some fantasy world here. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Every post I make you say that in your response. It's your mantra, but it still hasn't made you right. If all of these ideas and market forces I champion weren't real, linux wouldn't exist, and I wouldn't have Ep. III spoilers sitting on my desktop. This website wouldn't be here either; you think we'd <span style="font-style: italic">pay</span> for a license for a message board like this? Clearly, I'm experiencing a part of reality you don't have access to, or are willfully trying to avoid acknowledging. Denial is not just river in Egypt. I don't "disagree with everybody else on this issue" either. That's another fiction you've made up. Since over fifty percent of internet traffic is bittorrent, and we all know damn well that the majority of it is copyrighted material, I'd say you're the one in the minority opinion here, not me. I could be wrong, of course, but that's a lot of traffic to explain away by any other means. The fantasy world is the one you're trying to cling to, the one the information age is starting to make irrelevant. Progress is too fast, and too important. Technology and art are not going to wait for the law. If law gets in the way, law gets changed, ignored, or ground underfoot. Just like p2p is doing today.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Pink Floyd's "Dark Side of the Moon" is still one of the top selling albums to this day. Their product produced 25+ years ago is still a viable and competititve product. Why should they not be allowed to reap the benefits of such a product? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Pink Floyd isn't making money on DSoTM. EMI records is. If the band themselves were making the money on it, I would be far more sympathetic. If some rapper wants to use a sound sample from DSoTM for his rap compilation he should hardly be financially liable for it, yet that is the way the law works today. That's ridiculous. God forbid we send our celebrity superculture hurtling back down to Earth to live with the rest of us on the same financial level. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> The "Big Media" people should take this opportunity and sell, at a reasonable cost, their product via the internet a la iTunes. I personally think people would pay a reasonable charge to download a FLAC music file or a MP3 encoded at 256k bitrate or any other media file of decent quality. Most of the stuff shared via public P2P apps are usually very poor quality and I think if the record industry approached this with some open arms they could take advantage of the situation. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I completely agree. The piracy is only a problem because the copyright holders refuse to provide customers with what they want at a price they want, and so consumers use alternative (and illegal) methods that happen to be financially devastating, highly effective, and nearly immune to law enforcement to do get the intellectual property anyway.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Rav, you not paying for material is just as bad as pirating it and selling it. It has the same effect: the people who created it don't get paid for it. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
No, it's worse. I've accepted money for someone else's property. That's direct financial gain. That's a different beast then snapping my fingers and making a duplicate of something for myself, or for a friend for free, which do not result in financial gain. Believe me, I've had people offer me money for things like modding an Xbox, burning them a DVD of something... I have not and will never accept it. That's where my definition of actual theft begins. Perhaps my morality remains an enigma to you; that's fine, just take my word on it, there's a big difference.
<br />

<br />
If your point is that by giving my friend a free copy of something I am denying the creator a sale, sometimes you're right, sometimes you're wrong. I always encourage them to buy whatever it is if they like it. Always. That doesn't mean they can afford it. They may buy it five years from now, or decide they don't like it and never buy it. Perhaps they can't afford it (Adobe Photoshop, for example). One download of Windows XP does not equal one lost sale of Windows XP, regardless of the phony math their lawyers would feed you. The courts have, finally, come to realize that themselves lately.
<br />

<br />
I would happily pay for most of the music I've got, if I could get it in a lossless, non-DRM format online, preferably on a song-by-song or subscription basis. You be sure and let me know when a music service offering that goes online. Until then, they won't be getting my money. I'm still waiting.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> hell didn't CD/Record sales increase over the past few years? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Yes, skyrocketed in fact and reversed a regression trend. I'd say that handily disproves their myth that copyright infringement is hurting their business. I see no reason whatsoever to believe the MPAA when they say the same thing about movies, and @#%$ them twice for lying about it. DVD sales have outrun theater ticket sales. Clearly, there's a disjunction between reality and that line of @#%$ they feed the judges in the courtroom.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
