			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Part of this is the fault of the MPAA and RIAA.  The RIAA fought mp3 format for a very long time, just like they did CDs and casettes, instead of embracing the technology from the beginning.  The MPAA is doing the same thing with DivX, just like they did with VHS.  If both had embraced the technologies from the beginning, the copyright infringement problem wouldn't be nearly as bad as it is now.  It would still exist, but I think the scope of it would be much more limited.
<br />

<br />
Raviel, as much as I agree with some of what you're saying, you're still rationalizing why it should be ok for you to pirate music and movies.  Like it or not, once something is released, it should not become public domain.  Public domain implies that no one can profit from it, and that's not right.  Copyright limitation to fifty years or so, sure.  No problem with that.  But the creator of the book/movie/song/whatever should be ensured their ability to make money from their creation for a long period of time.  What it comes down is, they made it, not you.
<br />

<br />
Please note I'm arguing against my own interests here.  Just because I like having the ability to do something doesn't mean I don't still think it's wrong for me to do it.
<br />

<br />
Flarestar Bladesinger<br />
